00:14:18,010 --> 00:14:19,891
Your dream state should be that if you're

235
00:14:19,911 --> 00:14:22,773
going to roll out a new process, by the time

236
00:14:22,813 --> 00:14:24,014
you're rolling it out to the team,

237
00:14:24,614 --> 00:14:26,455
every single person in that room that

238
00:14:26,495 --> 00:14:29,197
is affected by that process knows what's coming,

239
00:14:30,277 --> 00:14:32,318
was consulted, and had an opportunity

240
00:14:32,338 --> 00:14:33,839
to give feedback on that process.

241
00:14:33,899 --> 00:14:35,880
So you're not really imparting any new information.

242
00:14:36,581 --> 00:14:39,182
You are just pretty much telling them

243
00:14:39,222 --> 00:14:39,983
something they already know.

244
00:14:42,715 --> 00:14:49,560
So, you know, we had that rattling and we powered through it and eventually we ended

245
00:14:49,661 --> 00:14:54,484
up at what felt like two levels, you know, you're going to have to squint.

246
00:14:54,524 --> 00:14:58,227
You kind of had to like blindfold yourself and take a bite of that pizza and be like.

247
00:14:58,929 --> 00:15:04,371
Yeah, this could technically be pizza if I think about it really hard.

248
00:15:05,332 --> 00:15:06,972
But it felt like a big success for us.

249
00:15:07,172 --> 00:15:09,253
Again, these are the first levels many of us were making.

250
00:15:10,694 --> 00:15:13,195
And we were calibrated to the rhythm of what we were making.

251
00:15:13,315 --> 00:15:17,537
It really felt like the first stage of the project was completed.

252
00:15:18,577 --> 00:15:24,719
And armed with that confidence, we marched into the next stage of the project,

253
00:15:24,800 --> 00:15:26,640
which is four more levels.

254
00:15:27,718 --> 00:15:28,878
So let's make four more levels.

255
00:15:29,219 --> 00:15:30,059
That's our goal.

256
00:15:31,079 --> 00:15:33,320
And before we go and make these four more levels,

257
00:15:33,340 --> 00:15:35,561
we're gonna take a little bit of stock here.

258
00:15:39,443 --> 00:15:43,005
This stage of the project, the four more levels stage,

259
00:15:43,865 --> 00:15:49,047
is where we have the most impactful process adjustment.

260
00:15:49,107 --> 00:15:52,549
I call it the great adjustment state or stage.

261
00:15:53,589 --> 00:15:56,611
It is what the majority of the stock will cover.

262
00:15:57,833 --> 00:16:06,116
And it is a period of learning from that first figure out what we're making and getting ready

263
00:16:06,156 --> 00:16:15,359
for the next stage of just making everything. And this adjustment period, uh, we framed in

264
00:16:15,419 --> 00:16:21,421
terms of solving some very specific problems. So here's that, here's the takeaway and something

265
00:16:21,501 --> 00:16:27,123
that you will see reflected all the way cascading through this talk is alignment on the problem to

266
00:16:27,163 --> 00:16:27,383
solve.

267
00:16:28,710 --> 00:16:33,880
So what I mean by alignment on the problem to solve is try to get your team and try to get

268
00:16:33,920 --> 00:16:38,929
yourself as much as possible out of solution space, out of solution brain, solution mind.

269
00:16:40,833 --> 00:16:46,739
if you are, or if you, if you lead them to be more problem oriented and you can get everyone to agree

270
00:16:46,799 --> 00:16:51,984
on the problem, then first you activate their solution brain in a much better way, which is

271
00:16:52,024 --> 00:16:58,910
not just solving whatever problem affects them, but solving the general problem.

272
00:17:00,332 --> 00:17:05,436
Let's talk about some general problems. So this is a big one.

273
00:17:06,801 --> 00:17:10,164
And it is the one that pretty much keeps me up at night.

274
00:17:10,404 --> 00:17:16,408
This is the design team is hungry for more guidance, but as a design director,

275
00:17:16,468 --> 00:17:22,332
my role is to provide that guidance with a light touch and in a way that doesn't steal.

276
00:17:23,274 --> 00:17:26,737
from their creative freedom and their creative agency.

277
00:17:27,257 --> 00:17:32,642
Like I said, if I'm going to be sitting at night in bed thinking I'm an imposter,

278
00:17:33,323 --> 00:17:38,508
what have I done? How did I get this job? It's going to be because I'm going to be thinking back

279
00:17:39,489 --> 00:17:42,672
to this specific problem like 95% of the time.

280
00:17:42,692 --> 00:17:42,732
So

281
00:17:46,380 --> 00:17:51,063
Let's talk about some lessons that I learned in providing guidance and

282
00:17:51,103 --> 00:17:53,604
providing creative freedom to my team.

283
00:17:55,165 --> 00:18:01,049
The first lesson is that every single one of your teammates is a different

284
00:18:01,069 --> 00:18:04,391
human and needs something different.

285
00:18:05,232 --> 00:18:08,834
What I mean by that is not everyone likes to take direction in the same way.

286
00:18:09,615 --> 00:18:12,016
Not everyone likes to.

287
00:18:13,720 --> 00:18:18,003
to provide creativity or to be creative in the same way.

288
00:18:18,523 --> 00:18:21,765
So there is not one solution fits all.

289
00:18:21,925 --> 00:18:25,167
You will have to learn about the humans in your team

290
00:18:25,487 --> 00:18:29,130
and treat them like humans and engage in that conversation

291
00:18:30,190 --> 00:18:31,711
in a way that fits them.

292
00:18:32,892 --> 00:18:33,512
So get to know them.

293
00:18:35,053 --> 00:18:35,954
The second one, however,

294
00:18:36,334 --> 00:18:38,335
is avoid having too light of a touch.

295
00:18:39,410 --> 00:18:45,999
So this one's especially useful for me because I tend to be the type of person who is more likely

296
00:18:46,820 --> 00:18:52,406
to lean back and let people be creative than to give too strong of a direction.

297
00:18:52,617 --> 00:18:56,799
However, what I've started to realize is that

298
00:18:57,760 --> 00:19:00,181
that is doing a different type of disservice to your team.

299
00:19:00,882 --> 00:19:02,943
There is a reason if you're the design director

300
00:19:03,503 --> 00:19:04,764
that you are the design director.

301
00:19:04,784 --> 00:19:07,265
It usually has to do with experience or passion

302
00:19:07,745 --> 00:19:09,586
or with a gift or a strength that you have.

303
00:19:10,567 --> 00:19:15,148
And not only is your team expecting that direction, but they will learn from you and

304
00:19:15,168 --> 00:19:19,090
they will grow to be better developers by watching you provide direction.

305
00:19:19,410 --> 00:19:25,912
So you're doing a disservice to the team and to the game by depriving them of your expertise.

306
00:19:26,552 --> 00:19:27,172
So don't do that.

307
00:19:30,133 --> 00:19:35,015
A big takeaway for me was to expose your decision-making process as much as possible.

308
00:19:35,715 --> 00:19:36,436
What I mean by this is...

309
00:19:38,382 --> 00:19:43,163
Presumably, presumably, when you make a decision,

310
00:19:43,323 --> 00:19:46,704
you don't just pull it out of thin air, right?

311
00:19:47,204 --> 00:19:49,085
You go through some process in your mind

312
00:19:49,185 --> 00:19:50,585
and you arrive at a conclusion,

313
00:19:50,645 --> 00:19:52,685
and that conclusion leads you to making that decision.

314
00:19:53,746 --> 00:19:54,946
If you can capture the process

315
00:19:55,706 --> 00:19:58,367
and then speak it out loud to your team,

316
00:19:59,967 --> 00:20:01,867
you're going to do them such a favor.

317
00:20:02,768 --> 00:20:03,008
Why?

318
00:20:03,208 --> 00:20:03,648
Well, first,

319
00:20:05,244 --> 00:20:09,417
Team members tend to be stressed if they can't predict more or less what you're going to say.

320
00:20:10,554 --> 00:20:14,356
Second, by you exposing your thought process,

321
00:20:14,837 --> 00:20:17,178
your solution-finding process, they

322
00:20:17,218 --> 00:20:20,660
will get to replicate it next time when they're

323
00:20:20,680 --> 00:20:22,000
putting the next thing in the game.

324
00:20:22,040 --> 00:20:25,402
So they're going to be able to say, OK,

325
00:20:25,582 --> 00:20:27,964
what did Francisco want here last time?

326
00:20:28,924 --> 00:20:33,427
And how can I sort of preempt that to, or adopt

327
00:20:33,487 --> 00:20:36,068
his decision-making, adopt his thought process

328
00:20:36,608 --> 00:20:39,890
to make sure that I am successful faster next time?

329
00:20:42,139 --> 00:20:44,400
And then it's just going to create alignment much faster.

330
00:20:44,440 --> 00:20:47,780
Here's a quick example of, you know, very quickly.

331
00:20:47,840 --> 00:20:51,801
One thing I threw together one day is we were having this giant play test and we're getting

332
00:20:52,281 --> 00:20:54,722
lots of data in from players, lots of data.

333
00:20:55,382 --> 00:20:57,622
And the team was getting a little stressed because they were like, what are we going

334
00:20:57,642 --> 00:20:58,382
to do with all this data?

335
00:20:59,063 --> 00:21:02,443
And to them, I was just making decisions randomly.

336
00:21:02,503 --> 00:21:06,464
I was saying, we're going to listen to that feedback and that feedback and that feedback,

337
00:21:07,044 --> 00:21:10,045
but they didn't see any rhyme operation.

338
00:21:10,840 --> 00:21:13,202
for or to how I was making those decisions.

339
00:21:13,422 --> 00:21:16,284
So I put together a really quick diagram

340
00:21:16,984 --> 00:21:19,105
and I said, right, here's what I'm doing.

341
00:21:20,446 --> 00:21:22,488
If we're getting lots of data

342
00:21:22,548 --> 00:21:24,189
pointing in one specific direction

343
00:21:25,069 --> 00:21:26,370
and that direction is low scope,

344
00:21:27,030 --> 00:21:28,611
I'm gonna take that without telling anyone.

345
00:21:28,832 --> 00:21:30,012
I'm not gonna consult anyone.

346
00:21:30,052 --> 00:21:31,013
I'm gonna say, let's do it.

347
00:21:31,253 --> 00:21:32,214
Let's just save some time.

348
00:21:32,674 --> 00:21:34,195
Easy to do low hanging fruit, grab it.

349
00:21:35,436 --> 00:21:36,857
If we are not getting a lot of data,

350
00:21:38,657 --> 00:21:40,377
on something that also happens to be high scope.

351
00:21:40,517 --> 00:21:41,478
I'm going to archive it.

352
00:21:41,498 --> 00:21:42,678
You will also not hear about it.

353
00:21:43,059 --> 00:21:44,339
I'm just going to pretend it doesn't exist.

354
00:21:45,080 --> 00:21:46,680
And then these other two categories

355
00:21:47,141 --> 00:21:49,342
are going to result in meetings, conversations,

356
00:21:49,442 --> 00:21:50,322
decision-making.

357
00:21:50,642 --> 00:21:51,843
We're going to talk through all of them.

358
00:21:52,143 --> 00:21:55,224
And this is what you can expect going forward the next week.

359
00:21:55,484 --> 00:21:56,645
And that was a great week.

360
00:21:56,705 --> 00:21:59,146
People knew what to expect and it lowered stress levels

361
00:22:00,647 --> 00:22:02,007
about all this data that was coming.

362
00:22:02,027 --> 00:22:04,048
They didn't know what it was going to result in.

363
00:22:06,660 --> 00:22:11,761
My next piece of advice is to again, be problem focused and not solution focused.

364
00:22:12,681 --> 00:22:16,302
And when you're giving feedback, trying to focus on the problems you're trying to

365
00:22:16,362 --> 00:22:22,804
solve, you may describe what success looks like and you could, you could request

366
00:22:22,824 --> 00:22:26,585
the implementation of a very specific solution if you feel super strongly about

367
00:22:26,645 --> 00:22:31,567
it, but I would, I would lean on the side of giving solutions as examples of

368
00:22:31,647 --> 00:22:35,228
something that might work and telling the team, you may take it if you want, it's

369
00:22:35,248 --> 00:22:35,648
there, but.

370
00:22:36,582 --> 00:22:37,703
don't feel pressure to do it.

371
00:22:38,825 --> 00:22:40,226
Here's an example.

372
00:22:41,768 --> 00:22:45,111
Let's say that we're making an I expect you to die level,

373
00:22:45,171 --> 00:22:46,293
and there's a rope in the level.

374
00:22:46,313 --> 00:22:48,094
And there's also a knife in the level.

375
00:22:48,695 --> 00:22:51,198
And the rope is there because we want the player to pull the rope

376
00:22:51,939 --> 00:22:56,483
and raise some sort of device by pulling the rope.

377
00:22:58,216 --> 00:23:01,277
However, what we're finding is that players find the knife and they go,

378
00:23:01,337 --> 00:23:02,597
rope can cut knife.

379
00:23:02,697 --> 00:23:03,837
I'm going to cut that rope.

380
00:23:04,337 --> 00:23:05,197
And that's just not working.

381
00:23:05,878 --> 00:23:06,558
It's not supported.

382
00:23:06,638 --> 00:23:08,658
We don't let people cut that rope with our knife.

383
00:23:09,838 --> 00:23:12,919
So I could go to the team and I could say, here's what we're noticing.

384
00:23:13,159 --> 00:23:14,379
Playtesters are grabbing the knife.

385
00:23:14,539 --> 00:23:15,540
They're trying to cut the rope.

386
00:23:16,600 --> 00:23:19,500
Let's just make the rope a chain, call it a day, ship that game.

387
00:23:20,881 --> 00:23:22,001
Uh, or.

388
00:23:24,041 --> 00:23:24,642
I could say.

389
00:23:28,082 --> 00:23:28,722
Here's what we're gonna do.

390
00:23:29,242 --> 00:23:31,363
Let's walk in the player's shoes for a second.

391
00:23:32,944 --> 00:23:34,865
I am the player, I'm playing the game.

392
00:23:34,885 --> 00:23:40,568
I open the drawer, I find a knife, I pick up a knife.

393
00:23:41,889 --> 00:23:44,090
What do we expect the player to do once they pick up a knife?

394
00:23:44,310 --> 00:23:46,331
Well, generally the player will find a new tool

395
00:23:47,091 --> 00:23:48,112
and they will look around the level

396
00:23:48,172 --> 00:23:50,233
and they will say, where can I use this new tool?

397
00:23:50,833 --> 00:23:52,634
And what they're doing is they're looking left,

398
00:23:52,934 --> 00:23:54,895
they're looking right, they're seeing a rope

399
00:23:55,235 --> 00:23:56,496
and because they already had the knife,

400
00:23:56,536 --> 00:23:57,076
they're seeing a hat.

401
00:23:58,376 --> 00:24:01,418
there's a keyhole for my key, I'm gonna try to cut that.

402
00:24:01,878 --> 00:24:04,740
So we need to intercept them at that moment

403
00:24:04,760 --> 00:24:07,101
and prevent that realization from happening.

404
00:24:08,081 --> 00:24:08,982
I don't care how you do it.

405
00:24:10,062 --> 00:24:12,204
We just need to prevent that realization from happening.

406
00:24:13,064 --> 00:24:14,385
So what does success look like?

407
00:24:15,125 --> 00:24:17,526
The player never makes a connection, knife plus rope.

408
00:24:18,407 --> 00:24:19,868
How will you address that?

409
00:24:19,888 --> 00:24:22,069
I don't care, up to you.

410
00:24:22,589 --> 00:24:22,869
However,

411
00:24:23,711 --> 00:24:25,653
However, here's a possible solution.

412
00:24:25,713 --> 00:24:28,056
You could consider making that rope a chain.

413
00:24:29,117 --> 00:24:29,598
See what happens.

414
00:24:30,138 --> 00:24:30,819
That might solve it.

415
00:24:31,380 --> 00:24:32,621
If you don't want to take it, don't take it.

416
00:24:32,862 --> 00:24:33,422
That's fine.

417
00:24:33,923 --> 00:24:35,284
Maybe the team comes back and says,

418
00:24:35,505 --> 00:24:36,245
you know what we're going to do?

419
00:24:36,846 --> 00:24:38,588
We're going to let the player cut the rope.

420
00:24:38,828 --> 00:24:39,269
And I'd be like.

421
00:24:40,900 --> 00:24:41,441
That's awesome.

422
00:24:41,561 --> 00:24:42,161
Let's do that.

423
00:24:42,662 --> 00:24:44,163
Or they might say, we're going to get rid of the knife.

424
00:24:44,303 --> 00:24:45,684
And I'll say, even better.

425
00:24:45,704 --> 00:24:47,745
Fewer, fewer stuff to support.

426
00:24:47,826 --> 00:24:48,486
That's great.

427
00:24:48,826 --> 00:24:49,046
Right?

428
00:24:50,127 --> 00:24:53,850
So, so the tool that I like to use to surface these problems

429
00:24:54,050 --> 00:24:56,332
is this walking in the player's shoes.

430
00:24:56,512 --> 00:24:58,934
So taking the team on a journey and.

431
00:25:00,322 --> 00:25:03,925
asking it every step of the way, you know, what is the player thinking? What does the player want

432
00:25:03,985 --> 00:25:09,529
to do? What might they do next with the knowledge they have approved? And what I've noticed is that

433
00:25:09,809 --> 00:25:16,174
by running reviews that way, developers start also thinking that way when they're making the game.

434
00:25:16,374 --> 00:25:23,659
And so we start having fewer and fewer issues like this one. The key to all of this

435
00:25:24,547 --> 00:25:29,291
I think that the one takeaway that encapsulates this whole slide is this last one.

436
00:25:29,892 --> 00:25:31,573
There are many paths to victory.

437
00:25:31,754 --> 00:25:37,699
This is the true Zen moment for me as a design director, is when I can truly sit down and

438
00:25:37,719 --> 00:25:38,280
believe this.

439
00:25:38,680 --> 00:25:41,423
What do I mean by many paths to victory?

440
00:25:42,024 --> 00:25:42,504
What I mean is...

441
00:25:43,560 --> 00:25:47,984
My job as a design director is to make a great game,

442
00:25:48,124 --> 00:25:52,467
is to find, to find in the universe of possible great games

443
00:25:52,507 --> 00:25:55,229
that we could make, there are infinite great games,

444
00:25:56,030 --> 00:25:57,911
I just need to find one of them.

445
00:25:58,812 --> 00:25:59,252
So what do I do?

446
00:25:59,473 --> 00:26:04,476
I tell my team, team, this is what a great game looks like.

447
00:26:04,737 --> 00:26:06,378
We're trying to find a game

448
00:26:07,439 --> 00:26:10,641
that is defined by these parameters.

449
00:26:11,533 --> 00:26:14,274
These are the boundaries that we cannot escape.

450
00:26:14,314 --> 00:26:17,475
These are some non-negotiables you cannot cross.

451
00:26:19,176 --> 00:26:22,217
And then it's up to you to take me to that great game

452
00:26:22,237 --> 00:26:23,897
however you want.

453
00:26:24,137 --> 00:26:26,378
If you can truly, truly believe that and let

454
00:26:26,418 --> 00:26:28,739
your team take you there, you are going

455
00:26:28,779 --> 00:26:31,700
to be so delightfully surprised.

456
00:26:32,160 --> 00:26:36,682
So my takeaway here is there are many paths to victory

457
00:26:36,982 --> 00:26:38,063
that you cannot see.

458
00:26:39,093 --> 00:26:42,274
And if you empower your team to take you to victory,

459
00:26:42,494 --> 00:26:45,715
if you define the boundaries, if you describe victory,

460
00:26:46,555 --> 00:26:48,816
and then you just guide them in that process,

461
00:26:49,316 --> 00:26:50,476
then they're going to take you there

462
00:26:50,596 --> 00:26:51,936
and everyone's going to be happy.

463
00:26:52,737 --> 00:26:54,697
Maybe it's too wishful thinking,

464
00:26:54,777 --> 00:26:59,078
but this is the holy grail for me of game development.

465
00:27:00,439 --> 00:27:01,679
We're all trailblazing together.

466
00:27:03,187 --> 00:27:03,547
All right.

467
00:27:05,028 --> 00:27:08,791
The next problem we had to solve was that even though I

468
00:27:08,891 --> 00:27:14,355
preach problem solving, I have a solution-oriented brain.

469
00:27:15,615 --> 00:27:17,557
I'm just firing on all cylinders all the time.

470
00:27:17,597 --> 00:27:19,298
Solutions, solutions, solutions, solutions.

471
00:27:19,938 --> 00:27:22,220
So I need a way to capture those solutions.

472
00:27:22,660 --> 00:27:25,422
When they come to me, just put them somewhere

473
00:27:25,442 --> 00:27:26,683
so they can stop bothering me.

474
00:27:27,983 --> 00:27:30,585
So living agenda documents.

475
00:27:32,259 --> 00:27:33,900
Maybe, I don't know, maybe everyone uses these.

476
00:27:34,020 --> 00:27:34,340
I don't know.

477
00:27:34,420 --> 00:27:35,201
We came up with them.

478
00:27:35,241 --> 00:27:37,522
I feel like we would never use these before.

479
00:27:38,083 --> 00:27:43,886
Maybe we're just like in ancient times of game development here, but they're just documents

480
00:27:43,906 --> 00:27:48,029
where anyone can drop anything at any time to be discussed at the next meeting.

481
00:27:48,449 --> 00:27:50,851
So they look like this.

