00:29:20,978 --> 00:29:26,622
like C-level executives, like the people who will eventually sign the game and say, yes,

511
00:29:26,702 --> 00:29:32,565
this is shippable. Their feedback was coming too late in a cadence that was unpredictable

512
00:29:33,066 --> 00:29:37,649
and in a format that was hard for us to parse. That was not their fault, actually.

513
00:29:37,669 --> 00:29:40,050
It was mostly our fault. And then...

514
00:29:41,510 --> 00:29:44,834
they weren't getting follow-up on what they wanted follow-up on because they didn't really

515
00:29:44,854 --> 00:29:49,898
know what they wanted follow-up on. And so we had some really, really rough meetings where,

516
00:29:50,119 --> 00:29:54,963
where, you know, stakeholders would come to us and say, Hey, I didn't know this was the plan.

517
00:29:55,003 --> 00:29:58,927
I'm not on board with this plan. And it was just way too late for us to do much about it. And,

518
00:29:59,427 --> 00:30:02,770
and that just felt horrible. So we had to do something about that.

519
00:30:03,739 --> 00:30:08,481
And then we also had no avenue for the team to give feedback or people to give feedback, you know,

520
00:30:08,941 --> 00:30:13,823
as it came up whenever they wanted. And all of this was making people stressed out. Everyone

521
00:30:13,843 --> 00:30:18,045
was stressed. It was, we were stressed because feedback was coming late. Feedback givers were

522
00:30:18,085 --> 00:30:22,506
stressed because they were like, what kind of game are these guys making? It was, it was just not a,

523
00:30:22,606 --> 00:30:30,029
not a great situation. So, so the first thing we decided to do was to say, we're going to choose

524
00:30:30,129 --> 00:30:32,510
one person, one lucky, lucky person.

525
00:30:34,128 --> 00:30:38,072
and we're going to make them the owner of the feedback.

526
00:30:38,192 --> 00:30:40,995
This person will be in charge of solving

527
00:30:41,075 --> 00:30:43,037
and owning our feedback problem.

528
00:30:43,458 --> 00:30:45,400
And so we said, all right,

529
00:30:48,242 --> 00:30:50,605
if that sounds like you, raise your hand.

530
00:30:50,865 --> 00:30:52,467
And everyone took a step back and I said,

531
00:30:53,548 --> 00:30:55,390
me, give it to me, I want it.

532
00:30:56,867 --> 00:31:02,628
this problem, give it to me. So, so I became the owner of the feedback and my life became this

533
00:31:03,289 --> 00:31:09,391
for many, many months. All I was doing is saying, this person thinks this game is too boring. All

534
00:31:09,411 --> 00:31:13,712
right, put it in this box. This person thinks this thing's too yellow. Okay. Give it to the

535
00:31:13,752 --> 00:31:20,034
art director. This person saying that rinse and repeat, rinse and repeat. And I redesigned our

536
00:31:20,054 --> 00:31:25,616
feedback processes and split them into stakeholders and everybody else. So.

537
00:31:27,619 --> 00:31:34,623
stakeholders. We made a special document for them, which I am super proud of. And we told them,

538
00:31:34,723 --> 00:31:39,325
please play the game every two weeks. And you're going to put all your feedback, everything you

539
00:31:39,365 --> 00:31:43,007
want, please, everything you want. As long as you're playing every two weeks, just put it all

540
00:31:43,027 --> 00:31:48,410
in this spreadsheet. Just tell us your build number, tell us who you are, whatever you're

541
00:31:48,430 --> 00:31:53,473
playing and write your feedback. Just, just drop it in there, drop it all, drop it all.

542
00:31:54,493 --> 00:31:55,674
And I just ask one thing of you.

543
00:31:56,350 --> 00:31:59,212
You're going to go to this high priority column, the one with the little yellow star.

544
00:32:00,273 --> 00:32:05,056
And if you want follow-up, you're going to say, yes, please give me follow-up.

545
00:32:05,536 --> 00:32:07,498
And I promise we will close the loop.

546
00:32:08,738 --> 00:32:13,542
The other side of that coin is if you don't want follow-up, you need to be okay.

547
00:32:14,382 --> 00:32:16,604
Never ever hearing about this ever again.

548
00:32:17,024 --> 00:32:22,307
So for example, you can say, hmm, I don't like the position of this dial on this

549
00:32:22,347 --> 00:32:24,569
machine, I think it's not going to work out.

550
00:32:25,918 --> 00:32:26,619
Do I need follow-up?

551
00:32:26,939 --> 00:32:27,479
No, that's fine.

552
00:32:27,499 --> 00:32:28,740
You guys figure out what to do about it.

553
00:32:29,140 --> 00:32:30,420
And you truly need to be okay

554
00:32:30,480 --> 00:32:31,981
knowing you're not gonna get follow-up.

555
00:32:33,101 --> 00:32:35,082
And this worked wonders for us

556
00:32:35,102 --> 00:32:37,263
because all of a sudden we had a clear cadence.

557
00:32:37,303 --> 00:32:38,643
We had a place to collect the feedback

558
00:32:39,544 --> 00:32:41,444
and we had assurance that someone

559
00:32:41,605 --> 00:32:43,945
was reading this feedback all the time.

