00:35:12,917 --> 00:35:14,977
The best way is they're just doing my job for me.

606
00:35:15,798 --> 00:35:18,098
They're just, they're just telling me what do we need to fix?

607
00:35:18,158 --> 00:35:19,499
So the tasks just make themselves.

608
00:35:19,539 --> 00:35:19,979
That's great.

609
00:35:21,160 --> 00:35:24,601
So from, from engaging with feedback for so long, I learned two big things.

610
00:35:25,701 --> 00:35:30,983
The first thing may not surprise you is about problems and solutions is that

611
00:35:31,103 --> 00:35:35,205
people love to give feedback in solution form, so you might get feedback that

612
00:35:35,285 --> 00:35:39,366
says something like move the key.

613
00:35:40,503 --> 00:35:42,664
from the drawer to under the seat.

614
00:35:42,764 --> 00:35:44,384
That's a way better place for the key.

615
00:35:45,745 --> 00:35:47,265
And you might be tempted to look at that and say,

616
00:35:48,325 --> 00:35:50,346
nah, that's dumb and throw it away, right?

617
00:35:51,226 --> 00:35:54,087
What I encourage you to do is ask yourself,

618
00:35:55,228 --> 00:35:57,328
what problem is this person trying to solve

619
00:35:57,449 --> 00:35:58,129
with this solution?

620
00:35:58,149 --> 00:35:59,709
They're giving me a solution, which I don't like.

621
00:35:59,749 --> 00:36:02,190
I'm not gonna do this, but I do want to know,

622
00:36:03,591 --> 00:36:05,271
why do they want to move the key?

623
00:36:05,611 --> 00:36:06,592
So are they telling me that the key

624
00:36:06,612 --> 00:36:07,832
is too easy to find right now?

625
00:36:08,890 --> 00:36:11,031
Are they telling me that the key is too hard to find right now?

626
00:36:11,912 --> 00:36:13,413
Are they telling me there's too many things in the drawer?

627
00:36:14,193 --> 00:36:16,315
Or that we should put something under the chair

628
00:36:16,355 --> 00:36:18,496
because it's a great hiding place?

629
00:36:19,237 --> 00:36:20,958
So if possible, I'll go talk to that person

630
00:36:21,118 --> 00:36:22,339
and I dig a little deeper.

631
00:36:23,499 --> 00:36:29,383
And if not possible, then I try to as much as I can reverse

632
00:36:29,443 --> 00:36:31,605
engineer that feedback to see where it might be coming from.

633
00:36:31,865 --> 00:36:33,126
So think solutions.

634
00:36:33,206 --> 00:36:34,186
Sorry, don't think solutions.

635
00:36:34,446 --> 00:36:35,087
Think problems.

636
00:36:36,429 --> 00:36:42,854
The other piece of feedback is about digging deeper instead of pulling back.

637
00:36:44,415 --> 00:36:48,398
We all receive feedback in our lives, in our careers, at home, whenever.

638
00:36:49,199 --> 00:36:55,023
We all receive feedback or find ourselves in situations that make us uncomfortable and

639
00:36:55,203 --> 00:37:01,788
not unsafe, uncomfortable, and tend to pull back and say, I don't want to engage with

640
00:37:01,808 --> 00:37:03,149
that because it makes me uncomfortable.

641
00:37:04,922 --> 00:37:07,364
I will say that I have learned the most about myself

642
00:37:08,185 --> 00:37:09,966
by not pulling back in those situations,

643
00:37:10,006 --> 00:37:14,890
but instead asking, why does this make me uncomfortable?

644
00:37:16,652 --> 00:37:18,533
And if I can be truly honest with myself

645
00:37:18,613 --> 00:37:19,574
and answer that question,

646
00:37:19,674 --> 00:37:22,516
then I find that it leads to growth every single time.

